Conservative leader Byron Rhodes discusses how Melton Borough Council transformed its crisis after a fire destroyed its old offices. Local authorities now face severe funding cuts, with Leicestershire being historically the poorest funded council in the country. The government plans to replace grants with business rate allocations by 2020.
Pep Guardiola acknowledged his first Premier League season with Manchester City hasn't been good enough after their defeat to Chelsea ended title hopes. The Manchester City manager promised he'll improve in future, calling this campaign a "massive lesson." Guardiola risks his first trophy-less season, with only the FA Cup remaining.
Welsh minister Alun Davies withdrew plans for 10 marine conservation zones after receiving 7,000 consultation responses with strongly held views. The Marine Conservation Society called it an embarrassing U-turn, as 70% of responses supported the zones. Davies will instead review existing marine protected areas.
Boris Johnson, London's Mayor and prominent Conservative politician, announced his support for Britain leaving the EU in the upcoming referendum. His decision reportedly influenced currency markets and may sway undecided voters due to his charismatic appeal. Some observers suggest this positions him well for future Conservative Party leadership.
A First Great Western replacement bus carrying 50 passengers broke down on the A34 in Oxfordshire and was struck by a lorry at 00:30 GMT. Three people were hospitalized, one with serious but non-life-threatening injuries, while remaining passengers were taken to Abingdon police station. The southbound carriageway has reopened following investigations.
Scottish boxer Ricky Burns made history by becoming the first Scot to win world titles at three different weights, defeating Italy's Michele Di Rocco to claim the vacant WBA World Super-Lightweight title at Glasgow's Hydro. The victory marked a remarkable comeback for Burns, who had lost three of his previous six fights before Saturday's eighth-round stoppage win.
Adult social care services face a £1.1bn budget shortfall amid struggles to hire and retain staff. Since 2010, councils have seen £4.6bn cuts (31% reduction) to social care funding. Officials warn these cuts threaten services for vulnerable elderly and disabled residents.
Terminally ill actor Brian Rix, 92, has changed his stance and now supports assisted dying legislation after previously opposing it. The Mencap president feels like a "beached whale" in constant discomfort and has urged House of Lords to pass such laws. He wants legal euthanasia to help others in similar situations die peacefully.
Police discovered a significant arms cache in County Antrim's Capanagh Forest, including rockets, anti-personnel mines, and pipe bombs. The weapons, believed to belong to dissident republicans, were found by members of the public. Authorities said the seizure undoubtedly saved lives and prevented potential attacks.
Kenyan election results are delayed due to electronic system problems, forcing physical delivery of paper tallies. Uhuru Kenyatta leads with 53% against Raila Odinga's 42% amid ongoing controversies over spoiled ballots. Kenyatta faces trial at the International Criminal Court next month.
Formula 1 driver Maria de Villota lost her right eye following a test track crash at Duxford airfield. Her Marussia race car hit a support truck during her first test drive with the team. She remains in critical but stable condition after lengthy surgery at Addenbrooke's Hospital.
The US Supreme Court upheld President Obama's healthcare law in a 6-3 decision, preserving tax subsidies for low-income Americans. The ruling maintains Obamacare, protecting health insurance for millions and cementing Obama's major legislative achievement. Republicans vowed to continue fighting the law despite this decisive victory.
Russia implemented new social media restrictions requiring bloggers with 3,000+ daily readers to register with authorities and follow media regulations. Internet companies must provide user information access and store data on Russian servers for six months. Human rights groups called it "draconian" internet freedom crackdown targeting Putin critics.
Western Sahara welcomed Morocco's readmission to the African Union after 32 years, viewing it as an opportunity for cooperation. Morocco controls two-thirds of Western Sahara and considers it historic territory, while others view it as Africa's last colony. A promised 1991 referendum never occurred, leaving thousands of Sahrawi refugees in Algerian camps.
Arcade Fire delivered an energetic performance at Glastonbury on Friday, reviving spirits after lightning strikes forced all stages to close earlier. The Canadian band's two-hour set featured confetti cannons, dancers, and crowd interaction, with frontman Win Butler calling it their career highlight. Other Friday performers included Lily Allen, Blondie, and Paolo Nutini.
Mead, the ancient drink of kings and Vikings, is experiencing a remarkable revival in the US with commercial meaderies growing from 30-40 to approximately 250 in the past decade. Modern mead producers are creating refined versions that are less sweet and more diverse than their medieval predecessors, offering dry varieties and flavors with fruits, herbs, and spices. Inspired by the craft beer movement, entrepreneurs see significant growth potential in this relatively untapped alcoholic beverage market.
Lady Gaga will perform at Sunday's Super Bowl halftime show before 110 million viewers, promising a career-spanning performance. The article highlights memorable past halftime moments, including Michael Jackson's 90-second silent stance, Bruce Springsteen's camera collision, and Janet Jackson's wardrobe malfunction. These performances set high standards for spectacle and entertainment.
President Obama criticized David Cameron for becoming "distracted" after the 2011 Libya intervention, saying the UK leader failed to follow through despite the operation's initial success. Obama described Libya as now being "a mess" and expressed frustration with European allies becoming "free riders." The White House later issued damage control statements defending the US-UK partnership.
Dawn Purvis is stepping down as programme director of Northern Ireland's first private Marie Stopes abortion clinic after leading it since 2012. The former Progressive Unionist Party leader says it's "time to move on" and will join the clinic's advisory board. She believes she achieved significant change in Northern Ireland's abortion perception.
Ten-man Inverness Caledonian Thistle lost 3-0 to St Johnstone, leaving them four points adrift at the bottom of the Scottish Premiership. Steven Maclean scored the opener before Larnell Cole was sent off for confronting the referee. Liam Craig converted a penalty and Graham Cummins added a third goal.
Deputy First Minister John Swinney will address MSPs about Scotland's Named Person scheme following a legal challenge. The Supreme Court ruled against information-sharing proposals in July 2016, citing privacy concerns under European human rights law. The Scottish government remains committed to the scheme after addressing the court's requirements.
Neil Lennon has been appointed as Hibernian's new manager, moving from the English Championship to Scottish football's second tier. The appointment suits both parties, with Hibs offering Lennon stability and success opportunities while he brings proven experience. His primary challenge will be delivering promotion with a talented squad that recently won the Scottish Cup.
UK manufacturing activity contracted in April for the first time in three years, with the Purchasing Managers' Index falling to 49.2. Companies cited weak domestic demand, reduced overseas business, and EU referendum uncertainty as primary causes. The decline suggests manufacturing could drag on economic growth in the second quarter.
PSNI launched a murder inquiry after prison officer Adrian Ismay died from injuries sustained in a dissident republican bomb attack. The 52-year-old was targeted by the new IRA for his role training officers at Maghaberry Prison. Post-mortem examination confirmed he died directly from bomb-related injuries.
Prime Minister David Cameron is hosting an international anti-corruption summit in London, calling corruption "the root of so many of the world's problems." The summit will bring together political leaders, businesses, and organizations to expose, punish, and drive out global corruption. Attendees include world leaders and campaigners pushing for significant reforms and ambitious targets.
English doctors are being paid thousands of pounds by clinical commissioning groups to reduce hospital referrals as part of NHS cost-cutting measures. The British Medical Association criticized these schemes as "misguided," citing concerns about patient-doctor trust contamination. Critics worry patients may miss vital care, though CCGs insist it promotes quality practice.
A Chinese woman underwent three jaw surgeries after her husband divorced her for having a "fat face," but had to halt further procedures due to nerve damage risk. She sued the hospital for 1.7 million yuan but settled for 20,000 yuan after experiencing eating difficulties. The unverified story sparked outrage on social media.
Hertfordshire council bought £450 worth of water from a local landscaping company to refill Welwyn Garden City's Coronation Fountain. The historic fountain was turned off due to hosepipe ban restrictions. It will operate during June's Jubilee celebrations and July's Olympic torch relay.
Harper Lee's "To Kill a Mockingbird," published 50 years ago, remains her only novel despite its beloved status in American literature. According to her close friend, Lee stopped writing because she refused to endure the privacy deprivation again and had already said everything she wanted. The book initially faced mixed reception in her hometown but now brings civic pride.
Britain's Adam Peaty successfully defended his 50m breaststroke title at the World Aquatics Championships, completing a double-double by finishing in 25.99 seconds. This narrowly missed his world record of 25.95 set in the semi-final. Brazil's Joao Gomes Junior took silver while South Africa's Cameron van der Burgh finished third.
Parents of a drink-driving victim want life sentences and manslaughter charges for careless driving while intoxicated, saying current proposed reforms don't go far enough. Their son Wayne died in 2010 when struck by a drunk driver who served only half of a six-year sentence. The Ministry of Justice is consulting on increasing maximum sentences from 14 years to life.
Nine British nationals, including four children, were detained in Turkey while allegedly attempting to illegally cross into Syria. Their specific destination and intentions in Syria's conflict zone remain unclear. Turkish authorities are cooperating with British officials and will deport the group back to the UK.
A congregation at St Hilda's Church in North Yorkshire has spent £10,000 building heated bat lofts to relocate protected bats roosting inside their 11th-century church. The bats continue soiling the altar and furniture with urine and droppings, creating an appalling smell despite a decade of cleaning efforts. Natural England requires careful monitoring before the bats can be moved from this regionally important roost.
Baltimore's mayor fired Police Commissioner Anthony Batts, citing his leadership as a distraction from fighting crime surges since Freddie Gray's death in April. The city has experienced a 48% increase in homicides this year following riots and civil unrest. Deputy Kevin Davis will serve as interim police chief.
Asghar Buksh admitted killing his wife Nasreen by striking her repeatedly with a blunt object while she slept. He claimed diminished responsibility due to acute stress disorder after their 25-year marriage deteriorated and she planned to move to Pakistan. Buksh surrendered to police after the attack and faces sentencing on June 27.
UKIP's national executive committee rejected a call from party activists to deselect Welsh assembly member Michelle Brown, who was accused of being "abrasive and discourteous." The rejection occurred because the complaint didn't follow proper procedures. Meanwhile, the party approved eleven candidates for its leadership contest, including controversial anti-Islam campaigner Anne Marie Waters.
The trial of cult members who killed Wu Shuoyan at a McDonald's in China has begun. The 37-year-old was murdered for refusing to provide her phone number to cult recruiters. The banned Church of the Almighty God claims millions of members, leading to widespread arrests.
Debutant Adil Rashid took five wickets to bowl Pakistan out after they seemed set for a draw on the final day of the first Test. England needed 99 runs to win but fell 25 runs short at 74-4 when play ended due to fading light. Despite the draw, it was an impressive performance from England ahead of the second Test.
Archaeologists discovered a 6,000-year-old eco-home near Stonehenge, built inside a fallen tree hollow and used for 90 years. The sophisticated shelter featured animal skin walls, heated stones for warmth, and decorative cobblestones. Experts worry a planned A303 tunnel could damage this important archaeological site.
Egypt's internet activists, who established networks in 2005, sparked pro-democracy protests through Facebook invitations that evolved into real-life activism in Tahrir Square. While social media provided the initial organization and publicity, the revolution gained momentum through police violence and diverse offline community building. Activists emphasize that technology served as tools, but the human connections and physical presence ultimately drove the movement's success.
Edinburgh's winter festivals generated over £241m for the city during the six-week Christmas and Hogmanay period. Nearly one million people visited, with 890,000 attending Christmas events and 150,000 enjoying three-day Hogmanay celebrations. The revenue directly benefited local businesses including retail, accommodation, and entertainment sectors.
BHS's fate will be determined Thursday as administrators consider bidder proposals. Greg Tufnell, a retail veteran backed by Portuguese money, leads the rescue race to save 11,000 jobs. Without a successful deal, the 164-store chain will be liquidated and sold piecemeal.
A Welsh firm wants to introduce PooPrints DNA testing to help UK councils catch dog owners who don't clean up waste. The system would require owners to register their dogs' DNA through mouth swabs. Fifteen councils are reportedly interested in using this technology to enforce cleanup responsibilities.
Scottish sports funding faces a 20% reduction over three years, dropping from £65.1m to £51.8m. The cuts result from reduced government spending and declining National Lottery sales. Officials worry about impacts on elite athletes and community sports development.
Political parties are preparing for next year's Welsh Assembly elections despite public election fatigue. Conservatives gained confidence from recent results and plan to challenge more constituencies, believing their NHS focus resonated with voters. Welsh Labour will conduct an analysis of their performance while other parties reassess strategies.
Scottish teenagers in foster care are being moved too frequently, with almost half living with their third foster family. The Fostering Network warns that 750 more foster carers are urgently needed to provide stability for vulnerable young people. This instability negatively affects children's education and wellbeing across Scotland's care system.
Historical Chinese government documents reveal that Hainan gibbons were once widespread across half of China until about 150 years ago. Today, only 26-28 of these rare primates remain in isolated forest patches, living in just four social groups. Their decline correlates with human population growth and deforestation during China's demographic expansion.
All four schools operated by Telford Co-operative Multi-Academy Trust were placed in special measures within a week. Ofsted criticized inadequate teaching, leadership, and low expectations, with students underperforming at both Phoenix Academy and Lakeside Academy. The trust is considering alternative sponsors for all schools.
Over one million EU citizens signed a petition opposing trade negotiations with the US (TTIP) and a Canada deal. The petition cites concerns about investor tribunals that could allow companies to sue governments for policy changes. Campaigners worry this threatens democracy, public services like the NHS, and European standards.
Diageo's Distill Ventures invested in Melbourne-based Starward Whisky to expand into new export markets. This represents Distill's second whisky investment, following Denmark's Stauning Whisky last week. The investment will increase Starward's production and support their innovation pipeline development.
Ruskin College has cut three degree programs due to low student numbers, affecting 25 students who chose the institution for its support of disadvantaged and mature students. Students and alumni argue this contradicts the college's founding mission of providing education for working-class adults. The principal maintains the college will continue focusing on adult education.
An inquest into the 1976 Kingsmill massacre where Republicans killed 10 Protestant workers has been delayed due to a lack of available coroners. Senior coroner John Leckey is retiring with no replacement appointed, potentially leaving only one coroner in Northern Ireland. Victims' families are fighting the delay, calling for more resources to address this decades-old case.
Rare Leonardo da Vinci drawings from the Queen's royal collection are displayed at Nottingham Castle, featuring portraits, sketches, and technical works. The Royal Collection contains almost 600 da Vinci drawings, originally acquired by Charles II in the 17th Century. The exhibition runs until October 9th.
